<Document>
<name>Picos de Europa — Beyos Gorge</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Picos de Europa — Beyos Gorge</h2><p><i>Asturias / León, Spain · N-625 with AS-262 spur to Lakes of Covadonga</i></p><p><b>Carved-into-the-cliff road through one of Europe's deepest road-accessible gorges.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>69 km (43 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–October</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Narrow gorge sections with no shoulders, fog, low cloud, summer access restrictions to Covadonga lakes (shuttle bus mandatory in peak season)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>138</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Picos de Europa were named by Atlantic sailors who used these limestone peaks as their first sight of land returning from the Americas. The Beyos canyon, carved by the Sella river, is one of the deepest road-accessible gorges in Europe — the road is literally chiseled into the wall in places, with the river 200 m below. Covadonga is the holy site of the Spanish Reconquista: in 722, Pelayo defeated a Moorish force in the cave shrine, traditionally beginning the 770-year Christian reconquest of Iberia. The lakes above (glacial cirque) close to private cars in peak summer — a shuttle from Cangas de Onís brings you up.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Roman Bridge of Cangas de Onís</b> — Pre-Roman foundation; medieval rebuild. The 'Cross of Victory' (gold-clad oak from Pelayo's standard, 8th c.) hangs from the central arch.</li><li><b>Santa Cueva de Covadonga</b> — Cave shrine where Pelayo (722 AD) defeated the Moors — traditional starting point of the Reconquista. Image of the Virgin sealed into the rock.</li><li><b>Lagos de Covadonga</b> — Lago Enol (1,070 m) and Lago Ercina (1,108 m) in a glacial cirque ringed by Picos peaks. Buciello viewpoint 30 min walk; ibex sometimes visible.</li><li><b>Desfiladero de los Beyos</b> — 10 km river-cut limestone slot canyon. The road clings to the wall; in places only one lane wide between rock and drop. Pull off at any of the few turnouts to look up.</li><li><b>Mirador del Pontón</b> — Panorama south into the León side of the Picos — the Cordillera Cantábrica's high spine. Eagles and griffon vultures use the thermals here.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
